<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">📖 Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">The global average is one number. Chennai's reality is a different number. Today: bridge them.</p>
  <p>Why does regional climate change differ from the global average? Three reasons: <strong>ocean heat distribution</strong> (oceans absorb most of the excess heat, but unevenly), <strong>atmospheric circulation</strong> (jet streams + monsoon systems redistribute energy regionally), and <strong>land-sea contrasts</strong> (land warms faster than ocean). The IPCC's "1.5°C" or "2°C" headlines are global means; the South Asia chapter of IPCC AR6 Working Group I has the actual regional numbers — and they're often higher.</p>
  <p>Today is also the day you <strong>lock your adaptation challenge</strong>. From the 8 you've been considering since Block 5, pick one. By end of block, you have 2 sources gathered + one-line OPVL on each, ready to feed your <a href="/units/unit-4/assessment-chennai-climate-brief/">Climate Brief's Evidence section</a>. The Greater Chennai Corporation Climate Action Plan is your second primary source after IPCC AR6 — it's Chennai's official adaptation document.</p>
</section>

